docs.abstract: A growing number of companies like IBM, Cisco Systems and Microsoft have partnerships with Chinese companies with ties to the military, and experts are questioning those links.

docs.abstract: Analysts say Twitter’s cuts show something may be wrong inside the company. But when tech giants cut thousands of jobs, the hand-wringing is far more subdued.
docs.snippet: Analysts say Twitter’s cuts show something may be wrong inside the company. But when tech giants cut thousands of jobs, the hand-wringing is far more subdued.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the scheme of things, 336 is not a terribly large number when it comes to corporate layoffs. That is, unless people have thought you were the Next Big Thing — or at least one of the next big things that probably won’t be quite as big as Facebook.

headline.main: Daily Report: Putting Twitter’s Layoffs in Perspective

docs.abstract: A much bigger test for Microsoft will come during the quarter now underway, when a flood of new hardware running Windows goes on sale.
docs.snippet: A much bigger test for Microsoft will come during the quarter now underway, when a flood of new hardware running Windows goes on sale.
docs.lead_paragraph: Microsoft’s revenue may have fallen 12 percent because it sold fewer smartphones and copies of Windows. But its earnings rose and the company had strong growth in the right place for investors — cloud computing, a business that is intoxicating to Wall Street because it represents the future of technology.

headline.main: Microsoft Earnings Climb, Lifted by Strong Growth in Cloud Computing
headline.print_headline: Growth in the Cloud Pushes Microsoft’s Earnings Past Wall Street’s Expectations
